<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-514-552  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 514 552.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDN  August 10 1989 v34 n14A p8(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>OTDRs tackle dead zones, reach 30-dB dynamic range: HP techniquespreserve resolution over distance. (optical time-domainreflectometers; includes related articles on OTDR specificationsand applications)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wiegand, Jim.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Optical time-domain reflectometer (OTDR) innovations have maderapid advances in the technology's dynamic range and ineliminating 'dead zone' problems.andP;  OTDRs determine the integrityof a fiber-optic link by launching a pulse of light into the fiberand measuring the power level of backscattered light to determinelosses in the Rayleigh reflected component.andP;  The 'dead zone'problem results from saturation of the OTDR's optical sensor,which prevents detection of further reflections.andP;  Manufacturerscounter this difficulty by placing an extra length of fiberbetween the fiber under test and the OTDR, moving dead zones intoa fusion-attached cable.andP;  OTDRs also tend to lose resolutionacross longer distances.andP;  Hewlett-Packard claims to have solvedthis problem in its 8145A OTDR with a new spread-spectrumtechnique.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Hewlett-Packard Co. (innovations).andO;Topic:     Optoelectronic devicesFiber OpticsData CommunicationsTest EquipmentPerformance ImprovementNew Technique.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Representative OTDR manufacturers. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>